5CE7-65F2-4A83-8398-0602CCA5580A</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Tim</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Harries</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG020558%2F1"><gtr:id>BDA17C9B-2CD8-4EDA-A325-72995EE77C2E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Understanding householder responses to flood-risk</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G020558/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>People do not always respond to the presence of natural hazards&amp;nbsp;as one might expect. Dr Harries' UK-based research shows that surprisingly few take precautionary measures; many deny the existence of the risks, and some even seem to face the prospect of a hazard event with positive anticipation. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Dr Harries&amp;nbsp;specialises in understanding the reasons behind these behaviours and attitudes and in advising governments how they can encourage greater individual and community adaptation to natural hazards. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This postdoctoral fellowship will provide a platform for future research and teaching in this area, allowing the publication of some of the findings of this PhD and&amp;nbsp;the postdoctoral work in Government and at the Flood Hazard Research Centre. Particular topics include the role of anticipated regret and anxiety, the impact of the notion of heroism and adventure, and the consequences of institutional inertia for the flexibility of the policy response to climate change. During the fellowship, Dr Harries will also prepare bids for further research funding, drawing on the expertise of colleagues at King's College London to give these proposals a theoretical basis that integrates sociological and social psychological perspectives on risk.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>78156</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Article in Independent Newspaper</gtr:description><gtr:form>A press release, press conference or response to a media enquiry/interview</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>C179C89D-F9FF-4E8F-8C43-DF0E04A03A75</gtr:id><gtr:impact>not known</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>545d0901dbedd1.76321014</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/war-is-waged-on-developers-who-target-sites-with-no-flood-defence-8360289.html?origin=internalSearch</gtr:url><gtr:year>2010</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:desc